04817nam a22007215i 9780812203820DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132008pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013957119  a97808122038207 a10.9783/97808122038202doi  a(DE-B1597)449739  a(OCoLC)979627944  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0360402bisacsh04a973.71141 aCumbler, John T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom Abolition to Rights for All :bThe Making of a Reform Community in the Nineteenth Century /cJohn T. Cumbler. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: "Till Every Yoke Is Broken" -- tChapter 1. The People and the Times -- tChapter 2. "With Other Good Souls" -- tChapter 3. "All the Great Men and Men of Respectability Stood Aloof' -- tChapter 4. "To Do Battle for Justice and the Oppressed" -- tChapter 5. "The Issue Is Universal justice" -- tChapter 6. "Blessed Are They Who When Some Great Cause... Calls Them ... Come" -- tChapter 7. Bringing Together the Professional and the Political -- tChapter 8. "Public Society Owes Perfect Protection": The State and the People's Rights -- tChapter 9. "A Relative Right" -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Civil War was not the end, as is often thought, of reformist activism among abolitionists. After emancipation was achieved, they broadened their struggle to pursue equal rights for women, state medicine, workers' rights, fair wages, immigrants' rights, care of the poor, and a right to decent housing and a healthy environment. Focusing on the work of a key group of activists from 1835 to the dawn of the twentieth century, From Abolition to Rights for All investigates how reformers, linked together and radicalized by their shared experiences in the abolitionist struggle, articulated a core natural rights ideology and molded it into a rationale for successive reform movements.The book follows the abolitionists' struggles and successes in organizing a social movement. For a time after the Civil War these reformers occupied major positions of power, only to be rebuffed in the later years of the nineteenth century as the larger society rejected their inclusive understanding of natural rights. The narrative of perseverance among this small group would be a continuing source of inspiration for reform. The pattern they established—local organization, expansive vision, and eventual challenge by powerful business interests and individuals—would be mirrored shortly thereafter by Progressives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aAmerican Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package American Historyz978311041349608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220382040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812203820423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812203820.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041349-6  Penn Press eBook Package American History  a978-3-11-045954-8  University of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHA